What Are We Doing Here?
We are building a machine learning based breast cancer diagnosis system using the Wisconsin Breast Cancer Diagnostic (WBCD) dataset in R language, where we:

Train 5 classifiers — LR, KNN, Decision Tree, Random Forest, SVM
Compare them across 3 different feature sets — Full (30 features), Correlation-Reduced, RFE-Selected
Evaluate using clinically meaningful metrics especially Sensitivity
Test whether differences are statistically significant
Identify which features matter most for diagnosis
Problem Statement
Breast cancer is the most commonly diagnosed cancer in women worldwide. Early and accurate diagnosis is critical for survival. While many machine learning studies have compared classifiers on the WBCD dataset, most suffer from three problems: they use arbitrary train-test splits without statistical validation, they use all 30 features without questioning whether fewer features perform better, and they optimize for accuracy rather than sensitivity — which is the clinically critical metric because missing a malignant case is far more dangerous than a false positive.

Research Gap
Here is what existing papers do wrong or skip entirely. This is the most important section for your paper.

Gap 1 — No feature selection comparison Papers 1, 3, 4 in your references use all 30 WBCD features without asking whether removing redundant correlated features improves or hurts each classifier differently. No paper compares full vs correlation-reduced vs RFE-selected features systematically across all five classifiers.

Gap 2 — No statistical significance testing Every existing WBCD paper reports accuracy numbers but never tests whether the difference between say SVM at 97.2% and Random Forest at 96.5% is statistically meaningful or just random variation. Without pairwise significance testing across cross-validation folds, all comparisons are anecdotal.

Gap 3 — Wrong primary metric All existing papers rank models by accuracy. In cancer diagnosis, sensitivity is the correct primary metric. A model with 96% accuracy but 80% sensitivity misses 20% of actual cancer patients. No prior WBCD paper frames its evaluation around minimizing false negatives as the primary clinical objective.

Gap 4 — Python monopoly, no R-based rigorous study Every major WBCD comparison paper uses Python with scikit-learn. There is no peer-reviewed R-based study that combines feature selection, cross-validated comparison, statistical significance testing, and clinical metric prioritization together on this dataset.

Gap 5 — No explainability connection to clinical features Prior papers report feature importance as a side note. None connect the top features back to clinical meaning — for example explaining why concave points worst and perimeter worst matter biologically for tumor malignancy.

